@article{Unden2002,
abstract = {Investigated is the problem of determining what propositions are presupposed by utterances of truth-functionally compound sentences of Eng. Speaker, sentential, {\&} logical notions of presupposition are presented. Conclusions reached are: (1) Where S is a truth functional compound A {\&} B, A or , If A, then B, etc, {\&} P is a proposition that is presupposed by A or B, three classes of utterances exist. (2) Existing theories of presupposition, which conflate negative {\&} neutral cases, are falsified by large classes of counterexamples {\&} can be shown to be structrually inadequate. (3) The form that an adequate theory should take is as follows: A speaker who utters a truth-functionally compound sentence S, one of whose constituents presupposes P, indicates that he is presupposing P unless: (A) he explicitly withdraws his commitment to P; or (B) he conversationally implicates that he is not assuming P; or (C) there is some readily apparent, alternative explanation of why he chose a sentence with a constituent that presupposed P rather than a logically equivalent sentence with no such constituent. How to make (C) precise by formulating explicit mechanisms for suspending the speaker's commitment to P in neutral cases remains unsolved. Modified AA},
